entry.title: [iOS] Remove unused code paths in startup.
entry.content:
This CL follows-up on crbug.com/1346512, which added assertions to verify that some code paths in the startup sequence were never used.

As far as we can tell after ~10 months, those code paths are in fact

never used, so this CL removes them along with a surprising amount of

other attached logic.



Specifically:



In [AppState applicationWillEnterForeground:], there is code that

handles the case where the 'Start' init stage hasn't happened yet. This

is now just an assertion and the code is removed.



All of the code that handles the 'launchOptions' from

[UIApplicationDelegate application:didFinishLaunchingWithOptions:]

is removed. The launch options aren't being read by any code, so

there's no need to save them. There were conditions around whether

the app was in the background when they were saved, but the app is

always in the background at this point. The only thing that needs

to happen at the point that these options were handled is that the

app state needs to start its init cycle; that's now an explicit

method.



Accordingly, the LaunchOptions property in the BrowserLauncher and

StartupInformation protocols (which had the *same implementation!*)

is removed, as is its definition. There were some big hairy tests

to verify that AppState was doing the right thing in this process, and

those are also now gone.



Bug: 1346512

entry.title: Fix a crash in SubframeHistoryNavigationThrottle
entry.content:
This happens when multiple frames traverse simultaneously, and the main

frame has a navigate event handler that might cancel the navigation.

If an iframe is navigating cross-document and has a slow beforeunload

event handler, it may not attempt to create throttles until after the

main frame traversal has completed. In that case, it will try to get the

main frame NavigationRequest that no longer exists and crash.

entry.title: Tweak net-internals HTTPS-RR support
entry.content:
Noticed this in the process of aligning these with the spec.

net_internals_ui.cc was serializing some information that the viewer

wasn't doing anything with. But, in serializing the ECHConfigList (a

byte string), it turned each byte into a separate JS integer, which

is a bit unusual. Instead, just base64-encode it, which should be

more compact.



Next, rename, at least in the net-internals code, "endpoints with

metadata" to "alternative endpoints", which matches the spec's

terminology. See https://crbug.com/1416410#c8. A follow-up CL will do a

mass rename across the codebase. I've separated these out because there

is an actual behavior change.



This CL also tweaks the output in chrome://net-internals. The old output

was focused on ALPN, but HTTPS-RR/SVCB does a lot more than that. It

also uses a somewhat awkward phrasing of "supported protocol alpns".

Instead, simplify the JSON output slightly and just dump the JSON

output. We seem to already be happy outputting raw JSON, so may as well

do that throughout. Introduce each entry as an "alternative endpoint"

per the spec's terminology.



Finally, use Array.forEach instead of Array.map. When not making another

array, forEach is the method to use.



I've also trimmed the names of the tests slightly. The references to

"single host" and "multiple host" don't seem to convey much. (There's

just one host. The "multiple host" seems to refer to there being

multiple IPs.)

entry.title: [BSC]: Create BoundSessionRefreshCookieFetcher interface
entry.content:
This CL prepares for replacing the

`FakeBoundSessionRefreshCookieFetcher` with an actual network bound

cookie rotation request.



- It adds pure `BoundSessionRefreshCookieFetcher` interface.

- Updates the consumer callback to receive the result of the network

request in the form of (net::Error and response code). The consumer

should built their error handling based on this result.

- The expiration date of the cookie is no longer sent in the callback.

The rotation request will use the `Set-Cookie` header and may set more

than one cookie.

- Requests will be resumed when the cookie is updated in the cookie jar

or timeout (not implemented yet)



On follow-up CLs:

- Timeout will be added to ensure requests do not remain blocked

indefinitely

- `BoundSessionRefreshCookieFetcherImpl` will be implemented.

entry.title: [Tab Switcher] Speculative Fix for Split Screen Grid Card Size
entry.content:
Some Android R devices in portrait split screen have a span count of 3

which is unexpected. This leads to a change in span count when entering

or exiting split-screen while on the tab switcher which can lead to the

brief appearance of tabs overlapping during the transition.



The fact the span count is 3 rather than 2 in portrait split-screen is

a longstanding bug. The easiest fix for that is to use the DP width

based span count used by LFF as what is likely occurring is a

race or reverse sequencing between onConfigurationChanged and the multi

window status updating causing the bug.



The other fix contained in this CL is to trigger a layout update

before updating the grid card sizes so that the grid cards resize after

having enough space rather than before the layout is resized this should

fix the overlap issue, but will not address the span count bug.



Since I do not have a device or emulator that reproduces this issue

I cannot guarantee these fixes will work, but to me these seem like the

only likely solutions.

entry.title: Fix a bug that swapped GenerateBid dependency latency metics.
entry.content:
A bug in BidderWorklet::DeliverBidCallbackOnUserThread inadvertently

swapped a pair of the GenerateBidDependencyLatencies. There was test

coverage, but the tests were unfortunately also wrong. As a result,

promises latency was recorded as trusted_signals latency and

trusted_signals latency was recorded as promises latency. This affected

the following metrics:

- MeanGenerateBidTrustedBiddingSignalsLatencyInMillis

- MaxGenerateBidTrustedBiddingSignalsLatencyInMillis

- MeanGenerateBidTrustedBiddingSignalsCriticalPathLatencyInMillis

- NumGenerateBidTrustedBiddingSignalsOnCriticalPath

- MeanGenerateBidConfigPromisesLatencyInMillis

- MaxGenerateBidConfigPromisesLatencyInMillis

- MeanGenerateBidConfigPromisesCriticalPathLatencyInMillis

- NumGenerateBidConfigPromisesOnCriticalPath



To account for the changed meaning of some of these metrics, this change

renames the `AdsInterestGroup.AuctionLatency` metric to `AdsInterestGroup.AuctionLatency.V2`. Any analysis that doesn't use the above metrics can UNION ALL these events together to analyze more data during the rollout of this fix.

entry.title: Fix PasswordGenerationControllerImpl::OnAutomaticGenerationAvailable
entry.content:
crash



The crash happens because the check here

https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/refs/heads/main:chrome/browser/password_manager/android/password_generation_controller_impl.cc;l=93;drc=fd3f62c28e3416868f06728ca813d394cfe9b963

started to fail after the CL

https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4466290.

The mentioned CL has the side effect that

`OnAutomaticGenerationAvailable` may be now called repeatedly for the

same focused field. I couldn't reproduce the crash, but most probably

what happens is that the repetitive call to `OnAutomaticGenerationAvailable` is received while the password

generation dialog is already shown. There is a check in `ShowDialog`

here https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/refs/heads/main:chrome/browser/password_manager/android/password_generation_controller_impl.cc;l=219;drc=fd3f62c28e3416868f06728ca813d394cfe9b963,

which guards against calling to show the dialog twice, so I consider the CHECK in the `OnAutomaticGenerationAvailable` excessive.
